    "instruction": "Load log.csv and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-21 06:28:36 UTC — 2024-01-21 06:58:36 UTC. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute: window_count (rows in window), sum_value, mean_value, and earliest_timestamp_utc where value>0 (or None if no positive values). Only include log_name values that contain 'error' or 'row_count' (case-sensitive as in file). Return a compact table sorted by sum_value descending and limit to top 20 rows. Also include overall per-cmdb_id aggregates over those log_names: total_error_sum (sum of values for log_name containing 'error'), mean_row_count (mean of values for log_name 'log.row_count' when present). Return both tables (per (cmdb_id,log_name) and per cmdb_id) in text/csv-like compact form." }

{
    "analysis": "You filtered logs for the incident window and found no error_count activity (all zeros) and normal-to-high traffic (log.row_count) continuing across most services with first positive timestamps around 2024-01-21T06:31:00Z. Metric anomaly counts flagged many socket/diskio/mem KPIs with earliest anomalies ~06:31:00Z as well, but many (cmdb_id,kpi) pairs reported identical counts for high/low anomalies (25/25), which suggests thresholding artifacts (P95==P05 or constant series) that need inspection. Traces and error_logs are empty, so we must rely on metrics and logs. The pattern — simultaneous socket and diskio anomalies across many services starting ~06:31 and no application error spikes — points toward a network-level issue (socket errors or packet loss) or a cluster-wide I/O anomaly. To decide between network-related (socket/packet) vs disk I/O, we need to inspect raw metric values and their breach severity around the start time for the top candidate KPIs (socket and diskio) to see which resource shows the most significant deviation from thresholds and whether anomalies are spikes or sustained. Next step: retrieve raw time series within the window for a focused set of candidate component-KPIs (socket and diskio for database and messaging services, plus socket for key services) annotated with their pre-computed global P95/P05 so we can evaluate severity and temporal continuity.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For these component-KPI pairs: user-socket, catalogue-socket, rabbitmq-socket, rabbitmq-diskio, session-db-socket, session-db-diskio, queue-master-socket, orders-db-socket, carts-db-socket: compute global_p95 and global_p05 using the full series for each pair (do NOT restrict to window). Then filter and return all metric rows for these pairs within the incident window 2024-01-21 06:28:36 UTC — 2024-01-21 06:58:36 UTC. For each row include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, timestamp_utc (ISO), value, global_p95, global_p05, is_high (value >= global_p95), is_low (value <= global_p05). Sort by (cmdb_id, kpi_name, timestamp). Limit total returned rows to 200. Return a compact table (CSV-like text) only." }

{
    "analysis": "You inspected selected metric series in the incident window and found many KPI series are essentially constant (their values equal global P05 and P95), which makes the simple >=P95 / <=P05 anomaly rule produce misleading dual flags. Log analysis showed no error_count activity and continuous row_count (traffic) across services, with first positive log samples clustered at ~2024-01-21T06:31:00Z — matching the earliest metric anomalies. Because traces and error_logs are empty, we must rely on metric severity (magnitude of deviation from thresholds) to identify the true faulty component. To do that we need to quantify how far metric values in-window deviate from their global thresholds (relative breach). This will let us pick the component-KPIs with the largest, sustained deviations (not the threshold-equal constant series). The next step is to compute global P95/P05 for all (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full series, then for the incident window calculate window_max, window_min, and the relative breach percentages for high and low deviations, and rank component-KPIs by the largest relative breach to prioritize the root-cause candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute global_p95 and global_p05 using the full available series (do NOT restrict to the window). Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-21 06:28:36 UTC — 2024-01-21 06:58:36 UTC. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) present in the window compute: window_count, window_max, window_min, earliest_timestamp_of_window_extreme (earliest timestamp where value==window_max or value==window_min), max_breach_pct = (window_max - global_p95)/global_p95 if window_max > global_p95 else 0, min_breach_pct = (global_p05 - window_min)/global_p05 if window_min < global_p05 and global_p05>0 else 0. Also compute peak_breach_pct = max(max_breach_pct, min_breach_pct). Return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p05, window_count, window_max, window_min, peak_breach_pct, earliest_timestamp_of_window_extreme_utc. Sort by peak_breach_pct descending and limit to top 20 rows. Output as CSV-like text." }

{
    "analysis": "You've already computed global thresholds and identified metric anomalies concentrated around 2024-01-21T06:31:00Z. The largest relative metric breach is carts — cpu (very large spike), followed by rabbitmq-exporter CPU and queue-master CPU/diskio; several DB diskio series also show notable breaches. Log analysis so far showed no error_count increases, and most services continued to report log.row_count during the window; however carts had fewer in-window samples (19 vs 25), which could indicate reduced throughput there. Since traces and error_logs are absent, we must use logs to decide whether the metrics' resource anomalies correspond to an application-level throughput drop. To strengthen the root-cause claim (e.g., carts CPU spike caused reduced carts throughput and thus system impairment), compare each service's baseline (global) mean of log.row_count with its incident-window mean to identify significant drops in traffic. A large drop in carts row_count concurrent with a carts CPU spike around 06:31:00Z would corroborate carts as the root-cause component and CPU spike as the reason. The next step is to compute baseline vs window row_count means and percent drop per cmdb_id for log.row_count.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv. For each cmdb_id that has log.row_count entries: (1) compute baseline_mean_row_count using the full available series (all timestamps), (2) compute window_mean_row_count restricted to the incident window 2024-01-21 06:28:36 UTC — 2024-01-21 06:58:36 UTC (use previously-filtered window), (3) compute drop_pct = (baseline_mean_row_count - window_mean_row_count)/baseline_mean_row_count (only when baseline_mean_row_count>0). Also return window_count and earliest positive timestamp in the window for log.row_count. Return a compact table sorted by drop_pct descending (largest drops first) with columns: cmdb_id, baseline_mean_row_count, window_mean_row_count, drop_pct, window_count, earliest_pos_timestamp_utc. Limit to top 20 rows." }

I conclude the most likely root cause is a sustained, large CPU spike on the carts service starting at ~2024-01-21T06:31:00Z, with no concurrent application error or traffic drop observed — so the root cause is carts experiencing high CPU usage.

